transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling.

Speaker 2: This is John.

Speaker 1: How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: You're on.

Speaker 2: My name is Winston Hardy.

Speaker 1: I'm calling in relation to my purchase I made when I was, well, I made a purchase, right?

Speaker 2: Before making that purchase, I went into my account, and I updated my new address, okay?

Speaker 1: Now, and I made a purchase sometime thereafter.

Speaker 2: However, the purchase I made was sent to my old address, and when I got that update yesterday

Speaker 1: saying that the delivery failed because I'm not leaving that address anymore.

Speaker 2: But I have updated the new address prior to making the purchase.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: I can help you, sir.

Speaker 1: Give me one second.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: So, should the address be 1477 Northwest 60th Avenue, Apartment 2?

Speaker 2: Yes.

Speaker 1: Was that the address that was sent on it?

Speaker 2: Yeah, that's the address we sent it to.

Speaker 1: I see that it's saying it's returned to sender because they say that there's nobody there.

Speaker 2: Have you talked to the post office about, like, that you live there?

Speaker 1: No, I don't have to talk to the post office about it.

Speaker 2: That's the address I gave.

Speaker 1: So, I don't know why would they say it's vacant.

Speaker 2: They say it's vacant.

Speaker 1: You've got to talk to them.

Speaker 2: So, we'll resend it, but you've got to talk to them so they get that issue cleared up before we resend it.

Speaker 1: How can I talk to them?

Speaker 2: I don't understand.

Speaker 1: Just like you called me, you call your post office and you tell them,

Speaker 2: Sir, I live at this address.

Speaker 1: You should not be marking things as vacant.

Speaker 2: Can you fix that in your system?

Speaker 1: You have to talk to the post office.

Speaker 2: Call them and tell them you live there.

Speaker 1: All right.

Speaker 2: All right.

Speaker 1: This is what I'm saying.

Speaker 2: I understand, sir.

Speaker 1: You're not listening.

Speaker 2: This is not something on my end.

Speaker 1: We have the right address.

Speaker 2: You need to talk to your post office.

Speaker 1: They don't think anybody lives there, so that's why they returned it.

Speaker 2: I cannot help you with this until you talk to the post office.

Speaker 1: Please call them.

Speaker 2: Have a good day.
